ribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Polish, Slovenian, Czech, Sorbian, and Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): from Slavic <i>brus</i> ‘whetstone’, presumably a metonymic occupational name for someone who honed or sharpened blades; possibly also a nickname for a clumsy or coarse fellow. Compare   Bruss  .","Slovenian: from an old dialect short form of the personal name <i>Ambrož</i> (see   Ambrose  ). Compare   Bruss  .","French: topographic name for someone living on a heath, from Occitan <i>brusc</i> ‘heather’, or a habitational name from (Le/Les) Brus, the name of several places in southern France."],"variants":[{"name":"Bruss","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Eldor, Reinhard, Rudie, Wilhelm.","German (also <b>Brüss</b>): from a short form of the medieval personal name <i>Ambrosius</i> (see   Ambrose  ).","Americanized or Germanized form of Polish, Slovenian, Czech, Sorbian, and Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic)   Brus  , meaning ‘whetstone’ and, as a Slovenian name, also ‘Ambrose’."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["Formed from Margaret."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Brus was born in 1255, in England, United Kingdom. She had at least 2 sons with John de Shelton. She died in 1332, in her hometown, at the age of 77."},"et":{"1255–1332":"1255–1332","1247–1331":"1247–1331","1302–1333":"1302–1333","1315–1378":"1315–1378","1315":"1315","1302":"1302","1247":"1247","1378":"1378","1333":"1333","1255":"1255","1332":"1332","1331":"1331","Shelton, Norfolk, England":"Shelton, Norfolk, England","Stradbroke, Hartismere, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Stradbroke, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1255–1332":"1255–1332","1247–1331":"1247–1331","1302–1333":"1302–1333","1315–1378":"1315–1378","1315":"1315","1302":"1302","1247":"1247","1378":"1378","1333":"1333","1255":"1255","1332":"1332","1331":"1331","Shelton, Norfolk, England":"Shelton, Norfolk, England","Stradbroke, Hartismere, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Stradbroke, Suffolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England, United Kingdom":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1255–1332":"1255–1332","1247–1331":"1247–1331","1302–1333":"1302–1333","1315–1378":"1315–1378","1315":"1315","1302":"1302","1247":"1247","1378":"1378","1333":"1333","1255":"1255","1332":"1332","1331":"1331","Shelton, Norfolk, England":"Shelton, Norfolk, Angleterre","Stradbroke, Hartismere, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Stradbroke, Suffolk, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","England, United Kingdom":"Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Margaret Brus est née en 1255, à Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Elle a eu au moins 2 fils avec J